# Repository Guidelines

## Project Structure & Module Organization
- Primary docs live in `product/`, `sprints/`, `technical/`, `business/`, `workflows/`, `meetings/`, and `docs/`.
- DevOps and infra are under `technical/infrastructure/` (Azure Bicep, CI/CD, env strategy, secrets, migrations).
- Utility scripts are in `scripts/` (see `scripts/README.md`).
- GitHub workflows and templates are in `.github/`. Example Node assets exist in `fundraising/`.

## Build, Test, and Development Commands
- Docs to DOCX (Pandoc):
  - Install: `powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File scripts\install-pandoc.ps1`
  - Convert (from a docs folder): `..\scripts\convert-to-docx.bat`
- Docker build (sanity check):
  - Python: `docker build -f Dockerfile.python -t saas202511:test .`
  - Node: `docker build -f Dockerfile.node -t saas202511:test .`
- Tests (auto-detected in CI):
  - Python: `pytest --cov`
  - Node: `npm ci && npm test`

## Coding Style & Naming Conventions
- Editor config: see `.editorconfig` (UTF-8, LF, final newline).
  - JSON/YAML/JS/TS: 2 spaces; Python: 4 spaces.
- Python: snake_case for functions/vars; PascalCase for classes.
- JS/TS: camelCase for functions/vars; PascalCase for classes; prefer `const`/`let`.
- Docs: kebab-case filenames. ADRs in `technical/adr/` as `YYYY-MM-DD-title.md` or sequential `NNN-title.md`.

## Testing Guidelines
- Python: use `pytest`; name tests `tests/test_*.py`. Aim for meaningful coverage; prefer `pytest-cov` locally/CI.
- Node: use your projectâ€™s test runner (e.g., Jest/Vitest); name tests `*.spec.(js|ts)`.
- Services: if needed, mirror CI service URLs (Postgres/Redis) via env vars.

## Commit & Pull Request Guidelines
- Commits: imperative mood, concise scope. Conventional Commits are welcome (e.g., `feat:`, `fix:`).
- PRs: use `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`. Include description, linked issues (`Closes #123`), testing notes, and screenshots for doc/UI updates.
- Keep changes small and template-aligned; update relevant docs when scripts or processes change.

## Security & Configuration Tips
- Do not commit secrets. Start from `.env.example` and follow `technical/infrastructure/SECRETS-MANAGEMENT.md`.
- For Azure deployment and CI/CD, see `technical/infrastructure/` guides and `.github/workflows/`.

## Agent-Specific Instructions
- Keep edits scoped; avoid unrelated refactors or reformatting.
- Place new automation in `scripts/` and document usage in `scripts/README.md`.
- For architecture/process changes, add ADRs and cross-link to PRDs and sprint items.

